        "biography": {
            "errors": [],
            "value": "In September 2005, I was awarded as MSc by the University State Campinas for my thesis \u201cCharacterization and fabrication of waveguide to short optical amplifier based in germanium-tellurite glasses\u201d. I was supervised by Dr. Luiz Carlos Barbosa. My research was supported by a CNPq (National Council for Scientific and Technological Development, Brazil) scholarship. \nIn October 2009, I was awarded a Ph.D. by the Federal University of S\u00e3o Carlos for my thesis \u201cStudy of Quantum Effects in Josephson Junctions Networks SNS and SIS through Vortices Induction\u201d. I was supervised by Dr. Fernando Araujo-Moreira and Dr. Sergei Sergeenkov. My research was supported by a CNPq (National Council for Scientific and Technological Development, Brazil) scholarship. \nDuring my Ph.D. I gained experience using the following techniques: magnetic susceptibility measurements as a function of the temperature or frequency, transport measurements with and without magnetic field at cryogenic temperatures with a superconducting quantum interference device - SQUID, resistivity measurements as a function of the temperature with and without an applied magnetic field, and fabrication of superconducting using the Pechini method. I have published 13 articles from my Ph.D. research.\nIn June 2009, I was awarded a four-year research fellowship from FAPESP (S\u00e3o Paulo Research Foundation, Brazil) for the project \u201cPlanar waveguide for optical communication from plasmonics\u201d, to be undertaken at the Physics Institute of S\u00e3o Carlos (IFSC), University of S\u00e3o Paulo, supervised by the Dr. Euclydes Marega Jr.\nDuring this fellowship, I developed research in plasmonics, metallic nanoparticles and nanocavities interacting with rare-earth ions. I received training in nano-manufacturing with the Focus Ion Beam \u2013 FIB, thin-film deposition by evaporation, synthesis of metal nanoparticles and micro-luminescence measurements. Such nanostructures were fabricated onto tellurite and tellurite-germanate glasses, which are doped with rare-earth ions and also with embed metallic nanoparticles. Let me realized both experimental and theoretical studies of the quantum-plasmonics interactions.\nIn December 2011, I was awarded a scholarship by FAPESP to research the Centre d'Optique et Laser Photonique - Universit\u00e9 Laval, Canada, for 6 months, supervised by Dr. Younes Messaddeq. During this time, I gained experience in the manufacture of optical fiber tips and in using a SNOM for characterization of plasmonic nanostructures.\nIn 2011, I co-supervised the research of an undergraduate student (Thin films of zirconia doping with rare earth).\nIn 2012 I co-supervised a doctoral student (Controlling the polarization of rare-earth emission via nanoantennas).\nI regularly review articles for leading journals in the field of optics and materials, including Optics Express, Optics Letters, Journal of Luminescence, Journal Alloys Compounds and Journal Applied Physics. \nIn 2013, I was invited to write a SpringerBrief, resulting in \u201cCollective plasmon-modes in gain media quantum emitters and plasmonic nanostructures\u201d.\nMy FAPESP Fellowship results in a total of 11 papers, 10 conference proceedings and 3 book chapters. I have also participated in various national and international conferences with a total of 34 papers. As well as participation in congress as SPIE-Photonics West (California-USA), Surface Plasmon Photonics 5 (Busan-South Korea) and Latin- America OSA (Lima-Peru).\nIn December 2013, I was awarded a Fellowship from CAPES (Coordena\u00e7\u00e3o de Aperfei\u00e7oamento de Pessoal de N\u00edvel Superior, Brazil) for 5 years for the project \u201cDevelopment and fabrication of nanodevices\u201d, to be undertaken at the IFSC, supervised by the Dr. Euclydes Marega Jr.\nIn March 2015, I won a call as Basic Science Specialist of the National Program on Basic Research, in the National Council of Science, Technology and Innovation of Peru (in Spanish CONCYTEC).\nIn April 2016, I won a call as Program Manager of the National Program on Basic Research of CONCYTEC.\nIn December 2016, I won a call as an Auxiliar Professor at the National University of San Marcos, Lima \u2013 Peru.\nIn 2017, I was nominated as General Editor of the \u201cRevista Campus\u201d, of the Engineering and Architecture Faculty of the University of San Mart\u00edn de Porres.\nIn April 2019, I won a call as Principal Professor at the National University of San Marcos, Lima \u2013 Peru.\n07/2019 \u2013 01/2020: Principal of the Postgraduate Unit of the Faculty of Physics Science of the National University of San Marcos, Lima \u2013 Peru.\nIn February 2020 a was nominated as Principal of the Promotion Office of the General Directorate for Research and Technology Transfer of the National University of San Marcos, Lima \u2013 Peru.",
